# WVU IENG 331 Honors Final — Team 7

Interactive forecasting application built with **Marimo**, **Polars**, **Altair**, and **statsforecast**.

## Live Deployment

- **Public URL:** `https://github.com/sw00111-wvu/wvu-ieng-331-final-7.git`

## What the App Does

This app lets a non-technical user explore Olist historical marketplace behavior and generate forecasts with confidence intervals.

Users can:
- Select a metric to forecast (`monthly_revenue`, `order_volume`, `delivery_days`)
- Choose a forecasting model (`AutoARIMA`, `SeasonalNaive`, `AutoETS`)
- Adjust forecast horizon (3–24 months)
- Filter by product category and seller state
- View historical actuals overlaid with forecasted values and uncertainty bands

## Local Run Instructions

```bash
uv sync
uv run marimo run app.py
```

Then open the local URL printed by Marimo.
https://molab.marimo.io/notebooks/nb_x4Jwn4cN4ogRnyEGx9FB56

## Repository Layout

- `app.py` — interactive Marimo application
- `src/forecast.py` — data loading, preprocessing, and statsforecast integration
- `docs/technical_writeup.md` — 1–2 page design and implementation writeup
- `data/cache/` — local CSV cache used at runtime

## Known Limitations

- First run may be slower while public Olist CSV files are downloaded and cached.
- Forecasts are univariate (no external regressors).
- Very narrow filters may produce too little data for forecasting; the UI displays a warning in that case.
- Deployment URL placeholder must be replaced with your team’s live URL.
